Section 1 — Language & Framework Rules
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════
# DIALPAD SUPER ADMIN DASHBOARD — CURSOR AI RULES
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════


## FRONTEND FRAMEWORK
- Framework: Next.js with App Router (TypeScript).
- All pages use the /app directory structure.
- Use "use client" directive only when hooks or browser APIs are needed.
- Prefer server components for data fetching where possible.
- Use Shadcn/UI components as the primary UI library.
- Use Tailwind CSS for all styling. No inline styles. No CSS modules.
- Never use styled-components or Emotion.

## BACKEND FRAMEWORK
- Framework: Node.js with Express.js (TypeScript).
- Never use Fastify, Hapi, or NestJS.
- All routes organized in /src/routes/ with one file per domain.
- All business logic in /src/services/ — routes must not contain logic.
- Middleware in /src/middleware/ — auth, validation, error handling.

Section 2 — Code Style Rules
## CODE STYLE
- Use ES Modules (import/export) NOT CommonJS (require).
- Use async/await for all asynchronous code. Never use .then() chains.
- Always use try/catch inside async functions. Never let promises go uncaught.
- Use const by default. Use let only when reassignment is needed.
- Never use var.
- Use arrow functions for callbacks and utilities.
- Use named exports for utilities and services.
- Use default exports for React components and Express routers.
- Destructure objects and arrays where it improves readability.
- Max line length: 100 characters.
- Use 2-space indentation throughout.
- All strings use single quotes except JSX attributes.
- Add trailing commas in multi-line objects and arrays.

## NAMING CONVENTIONS
- React components: PascalCase (e.g., ChatThread, AgentList)
- Files for components: PascalCase (e.g., ChatThread.tsx)
- All other files: camelCase (e.g., authMiddleware.ts, messageService.ts)
- Database columns: snake_case (e.g., created_at, agent_id)
- TypeScript variables: camelCase (e.g., agentId, threadData)
- Constants: SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE (e.g., JWT_EXPIRES_IN)
- CSS classes: Tailwind utility classes only

Section 3 — Database Rules
## DATABASE
- Database: PostgreSQL accessed via the "pg" npm package.
- Use parameterized queries ALWAYS — never string interpolation in SQL.
- All DB operations in /backend/src/db/ query helper files.
- Never write SQL directly inside route handlers.
- Use transactions for any operation that touches multiple tables.
- All UUIDs generated by PostgreSQL (gen_random_uuid()) not JavaScript.
- All timestamps stored as TIMESTAMPTZ (timezone-aware).
- Always paginate list queries — default 50 rows, max 100.
- Always add WHERE conditions on indexed columns for list queries.

## DATABASE PATTERNS
- Use pool.query() for single queries.
- Use pool.connect() + client.query() + client.release() for transactions.
- Always handle pool errors with try/catch and release client in finally block.
- Log all DB errors with enough context to debug (query name, params summary).

Section 4 — Authentication & Security Rules
## AUTHENTICATION
- JWT authentication using the "jsonwebtoken" npm package.
- Password hashing using bcrypt with salt rounds of 12.
- JWT tokens expire in 8 hours (JWT_EXPIRES_IN=8h).
- JWT secret loaded from environment variable JWT_SECRET.
- All protected routes use the authMiddleware from /middleware/auth.ts.
- Role checks done at route level using roleMiddleware.
- Never return password_hash in any API response.
- Never log passwords, tokens, or webhook secrets.

## SECURITY
- Verify Dialpad webhook signatures on EVERY inbound webhook.
- Use HMAC-SHA256 with timing-safe comparison (crypto.timingSafeEqual).
- Never trust user input — validate all request bodies with express-validator.
- Sanitize all user input before DB insertion.
- All secrets loaded from environment variables using dotenv.
- Never commit .env files. Always use .env.example with empty values.
- Use helmet middleware for security headers.
- Use cors middleware restricted to FRONTEND_URL only.
- Rate limit: 100 requests per minute per IP on all API routes.
- Rate limit: 10 requests per minute per IP on auth routes.

Section 5 — API & Webhook Rules
## API DESIGN
- All API responses use consistent format:
  Success: { success: true, data: {...} }
  Error:   { success: false, error: "message", code: "ERROR_CODE" }
- Use HTTP status codes correctly:
  200 OK, 201 Created, 400 Bad Request,
  401 Unauthorized, 403 Forbidden, 404 Not Found, 500 Server Error
- All list endpoints support: page, limit, sort, order query params.
- Never expose internal error stack traces in production responses.

## WEBHOOK HANDLING
- Webhook route: POST /api/webhooks/dialpad
- First action: save raw event to webhook_events table (always, even if processing fails).
- Second action: verify signature — reject 401 if invalid.
- Third action: route event to correct processor based on event type.
- Processors are in /src/events/ — one file per event type.
- Always respond 200 to Dialpad immediately, process asynchronously.
- Use Redis queue for async processing to avoid webhook timeouts.
- Failed events must be retried up to 3 times with exponential backoff.
- Log all webhook processing errors with event ID for replay.

Section 6 — Real-Time & State Rules
## REAL-TIME (Socket.IO)
- Socket.IO server runs on same Express server.
- All socket connections require a valid JWT (authenticate on connection).
- Clients join rooms by office ID and user ID on connect.
- Emit events: new_message, message_sent, message_failed,
  call_started, call_ended, agent_status, new_notification, transcript_ready
- Never emit to all clients — always emit to specific room or user socket.
- Redis adapter used for Socket.IO in multi-server environments.

## FRONTEND STATE
- Use Zustand for global state management.
- Stores: authStore.ts, officeStore.ts, notificationStore.ts
- Use React Query (TanStack Query) for server state and API calls.
- Never store sensitive data (tokens) in localStorage — use httpOnly cookies.
- Optimistic UI for outbound messages: show immediately, confirm on socket event.

Section 7 — AI Integration Rules
## AI ANALYSIS (Anthropic Claude API)
- Use Anthropic SDK: @anthropic-ai/sdk
- Always use model: claude-sonnet-4-20250514
- Max tokens per request: 1500
- Always include a system prompt that sets context as a communication analyst.
- Conversation history passed as user message formatted clearly.
- Premade prompts handled as templates in /src/services/ai.ts.
- Custom user queries passed through after basic sanitization.
- Never send PII to AI beyond what is already in the message content.
- Rate limit AI endpoints: 20 requests per user per hour.
- Cache AI responses for identical thread + query combinations (Redis, TTL 30min).

